On Nov 20, 2003, at 3:02 PM, Lasitha Ranatunga wrote:

&gt; I&#39;ve been solving this kind of duplication by creating my own 
&gt; assertions.
&gt; As an example, see my version of CalculateAgeTest below.  I&#39;m curious 
&gt; about
&gt; the pros/cons of each approach?
&gt;
&gt; cheers, lasitha.
&gt;
&gt; ----------------
&gt; package ca.bluejays.scouting.amateur.model.test;
&gt;
&gt; import java.util.Date;
&gt;
&gt; import junit.framework.*;
&gt; import XXX.BiographicalReport;
&gt; import XXX.PlayerFactory;
&gt;
&gt; import com.diasparsoftware.java.util.DateUtil;
&gt;
&gt; public class CalculateAgeTest2 extends TestCase {
&gt;
&gt;     public void testBirthday() {
&gt;         assertCorrectAge(30, DateUtil.makeDate(2004, 5, 4));
&gt;     }
&gt;
&gt;     public void testDayBeforeBirthday() {
&gt;         assertCorrectAge(29, DateUtil.makeDate(2004, 5, 3));
&gt;     }
&gt;
&gt;     public void testDayAfterBirthday() {
&gt;         assertCorrectAge(30, DateUtil.makeDate(2004, 5, 5));
&gt;     }
&gt;
&gt;     public void testDateOfBirth() {
&gt;         assertCorrectAge(0, DateUtil.makeDate(1974, 5, 4));
&gt;     }
&gt;
&gt;     public void testInvalidFutureDate() {
&gt;         assertCorrectAge(0, DateUtil.makeDate(1974, 5, 3));
&gt;     }
&gt;
&gt;     private void assertCorrectAge(int expectedAge, Date futureDate) {
&gt;         BiographicalReport biographicalReport = PlayerFactory
&gt;                 .makeBiographicalReport(&quot;Joe&quot;, &quot;Rainsberger&quot;, DateUtil
&gt;                     .makeDate(1974, 5, 4));
&gt;
&gt;         assertEquals(new Integer(expectedAge),
&gt;                      biographicalReport.getAgeAsOf(futureDate));
&gt;     }
&gt; }


To my mind, this approach is more explicit than the parameterized test 
case example.  That is, I prefer the level of test language used here 
over the language used to coerce JUnit to do it for me.  But that&#39;s 
just my mind...

